<subSubSection pageNumber="263" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="263">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="263">Note:</emphasis>
Tryon (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="263">Contr. Gray Herb.</emphasis>
194: 152. 1964) treated 1252.10 (LINN) as the type but Proctor (in Howard, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="263">Fl. Lesser Antilles</emphasis>
2: 185. 1977) argued that both it and the cited Plukenet plate conflicted with 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Linnaeus’">Linnaeus'</normalizedToken>
diagnosis and so designated a 
<typeStatus>neotype</typeStatus>
from Herb. Sloane (1: 127, BM-SL). The material in LINN is apparently identifiable as 
<taxonomicName authority="L." authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Pteridaceae" genus="Adiantum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pulverulentum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="263">A. pulverulentum</emphasis>
L.
</taxonomicName>
, while the Plukenet plate is said to depict 
<taxonomicName authority="Jenman" authorityName="Jenman" authorityYear="1886" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Pteridaceae" genus="Adiantum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kendalii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="263">A. kendalii</emphasis>
Jenman
</taxonomicName>
(Proctor, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="263">Ferns Jamaica:</emphasis>
241. 1985). However, despite its apparently unfortunate identity, the Plukenet element forms part of the protologue and therefore cannot be deemed to conflict with it. It is original material for the name, and so 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Proctor’s">Proctor's</normalizedToken>
designation of a 
<typeStatus>neotype</typeStatus>
is contrary to Art. 7.11. The name may be a candidate for conservation with a conserved type.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
